{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_brookland_ver01/data/sn84026749/00205696386/1930092601/0428.xml":{"full_text":"22\nARLINGTON COUNTY HEARS BYARS ATTACK CARTER GLASS\nRESERVE BOfiRD\nREDUCTIONS\nARE HIT\nIndependent Va. Democratic\nCandidate\u2019s Charges Take\nCenter of Interest Now\nARLINGTON, Va., Sept. 25.\nCharges that the Federal Reserve\nBoard is responsible for the pres\nent business depression, made by\nJ, Cloyd Byars, independent can\ndidate for the Democratic sena\ntorial nomination in Virginia, are\nthe focus of interest in Arlington\ncounty just now.\nByars declares that Senator Car\nter Glass has been a champion of\nFederal reserve policies in lower\ning the rediscount rate, to which\nhe attributes the severe business\ncontraction, and for that reason\nis unworthy of further confidence\nfrom the people of Virginia.\nBlames Glass\nByars says the forty-billion-dollar\nstock crash of last fall, which\nushered in the present depression,\nwas caused directly by the Glass\nsponsored policy of the Federal Re\nserve Board in contracting credits\nthrough the simple method of rais\ning the re-discount rate in the Fed\neral reserve system to 8 per cent.\nNot being able to pay this\nusurious rate of interest, member\nbanks could not borrow from the\nFederal Reserve banks, and there\nfore could not lend the ordinary\nnecessary amount of money for\nthe conduct of business, he says.\nThe depression which followed,\nsays Byars, was the inevitable\nresult.\nMitchell Episode\nByars points to the violent de\nmands which the Virginia Sena\ntor made on the Senate floor for\na raising of the discount rate,\nand to his demand for the resig\nnation of President Mitchell of\nthe National City Bank, when\nthat official threw $25,000,000\ninto Wall Street to stem the tide\nof panic, after the rediscount\nrate had been raised last October.\nFriends of Mitchell countered\nwith a demand that Senator\nGlass resign, but the damage was\ndone, the panic was on, and the\nbusiness men of \u2018America, the\nwealth producing units, agricul\nture, commerce and industry are\nthe victims, says Byars.\nThree Churches Get\nBequests From Will\nHAGERSTOWN, Md.. Sept. 2\u00ab.\nThree churches are named as\nbeneficiaries in the will of William\nH. Leatherman, who died last\nweek. The will disposes of an\nestate of $25,000. He left $1,200\nth St. Poul's United Brethren\nChurch of Hagerstown and SI,OOO\neach to the United Brethren and\nthe Church of the Brethren de\nnominations of Myersville.\n\u201cKing\u201d Jailed\nw W\n\nMb w.\ntK\nV1 I a\n1; M\nI IMrok I\nE' 7 w\nI 1\" i I\nT- Z \u2019.W\n1 v l?r\n9'4 I i '1\u00ab E\na.\nBflTa JW\nSBBHL 5; v VK\nHi 1\n.SRI\n-'Sb\nS 5 PH\nW fcjgj gHI\nWMay,.;JEEKLAO\nT \u201cKING\" JAN SYTUL\nt WHO CLAIMS he is. the\nj*'King of Poland\u201d is stopping a\ndays at Gallinger Hospital.\n\u2019He demanded a Polish pass-\nport yesterday of the legation\nhere, declaring he wanted to\nI get \u2018'back to his throne.\u201d\nWhen arrested he wore an or\nnate blue uniform, carried a\nsword, an umbrella, a SSO\nPolish bond and $607 in cash.\np MILITARY SURGEONS OF THE UNITED STATES 7n D. C. MEET\n\u2014will Wint\u2014\u2014W..- ME ~V\u00bb s\nmm f \u25a0t\u25a0 f u\u25a0MrMh\nM \u25a0FwaMiSRSiwKiKZKDI VSKJr\nt a*, 4\nM MSdtfL 99/ .Ji\nIr W I f VflWi VW\n\u2014-IT jfflk rj\n.L\u2014Sy 1 MM W?\nwKd .Wh- S '.lB\n.y-By /bBBBb,.\nBRISE- Wmmto\nSp'MBICT IHI' VB >i\nm o'\u2022 4 |K 7 j\u00dfa| i BBt BIM\nJE aiJ\u00dfi >'LiEk\u2014\u2022.-\u201c\" '\u25a1S I\nK.\n\nMRS. ARON AND MRS. I. F. FRISCH\nTHE ASSOCIATION of Military Surgeons of the\nUnited States opened its annual convention yesterday\nat Wardman Park Hotel. Maj. Gen. Herbert B. Crosby,\nDistrict Commissioner, and Brig. Gen. William H. Wil-\n\u2018TYPICAL GIRL\u2019\nRAGE TO END\nWith the \"deadline\u201d rapidly\napproaching, the Typical Wash\nington Girl Editor is being deluged\nwith nominations of girls whose\nfriends think they are-entitled to\nthe free trip to Paris being of\nfered by The Washington Times\nand Gloria Swanson, famous film\nactress.\nThe \u201cdeadline\u201d is at midnight\non Tuesday, September 30. All\nnominations must be in the mail\nby that time.\nPatent Girl\nFrom every comer of the busi\nness life of the city come the\nnominations. The patent attor\nneys think they can lay claim to\nthe Typical Washington Girl.\nMiss Lorraine Carey. 19, of 724\nSixth St. S. E\u201e a stenographer in\nthe employ of John Brady, patent\nattorney, in the Ouray Building,\nhas been nominated for the title.\nMiss Carey has been employed by\nMr. Brady for three months.\nMiss Carey is extremely fond of\nmusic and has a good voice. She\naccompanies herself on the\nukulele. She is a perfect specimen\nof health and is fond of all sports,\nparticularly tennis and horseback\nriding. She is an excellent swim\nmer.\nLansburgh Entry\nMiss Carey is 5 feet 5 inches\ntall and weighs about 120 pounds.\nShe was recently graduated from\nSt. Rose\u2019s Technical School with\nhonors in commercial work and\ndomestic art. She was considered\none of the most popular girls\nin school.\nLansburgh and Brother\u2019s de\npartment store also thinks it has\nthe Typical Washington Girl in\nthe person of Miss Margaret\nThomas, 19, of 1304 Pennsylvania\nAve. S. E. She has been em\nployed at the store almost a year\nand has the reputation of being\npleasing in her manner, ex\ntremely courteous, and efficient\nin business.\nMiss Thomas\u2019 backers say she\nhas a beautiful character, high\nideals, and a sunny disposition.\nShe is fond of music and has\ntaken vocal lessons for several\nyears. She also enjoys good\nbooks. Miss Thomas is a good\nswimmer. Her friends say she\nalso is a first-class cook and\ngood housekeeper.\nGrace Woodson Listed\nAnother entrant for the title of\nTypical Washington Girl is Miss\nGrace M. Woodson, 18, of 2407\nEighteenth St. N. W.\nGirls who want a taste of what\nlies in store for the Typical\nWashington Girl soon will have\ntheir opportunity'. Miss Swan\nson\u2019s latest picture\u2014\u201c What A\nWidow!\u201d\u2014will be shown at Loew\u2019s\nColumbia Theater beginning Oc\ntober 4 In this film Miss Swan\nson goes to New York, crosses\nthe ocean on the liner lie de\nFrance and spends a glorious\ntime in Paris. The Typical\nWashington Girl will traverse\nthe same route, visit the same\nscenes.\nStep lively, please! All nom\ninations must be in the mail by\n1 midnight on next Tuesday.\nTHE WASHINGTON TIMES\nNomination Blank\nThe Washington Times' Quest\nFor The Typical Washington Girl.\nI wish to nominate the following young lady as an\nentrant in The Washington Times' Quest for the Typical\nWashington Girl. z\n(Signature)\n(Address)\nName of Entrant\nEntrant's Address\nAge\nEmployer's name and address\nHow long employed there\nAttach on a ae pa rata ahMt a brief atatomrnt settlor forth entrant\u2019a\ngeneral health, athletic act!Titles, habits, eharaeter Ideals, extent of eda\neatlon: social, dale or philanthropic artl.ltles; and accomplishments In\nthe fields of hu.lness mnslo. literature art danelne drama, or domes\ntic science or art.\nSend nomination blanks torether with a rood photorraph of the en\ntrant to The Typical Washlnrtoa Girl Editor The Washinrton Times\nWashlnrton. I). \u20224D-\nNo nhotorraphe or statements will he returned.\nIs One of Them the Typical Girl?\n'\u25a0R*\nI\nF\u2019\" W X\nwMiBiBI\nX 5 w 1 v JO\nf\nm timDMmi J'\u00ab- x w .MW i?\nj;\nr< g\nMISS MARGARET THOMAS\nHERE ARE TWO MORE ENTRANTS for the title of Typical Washington Girl-\nMiss Margaret Thomas, of 1304 Pennsylvania Ave. S. E., and Miss Grace M. Woodson,\nof 2407 Eighteenth St. N. W. Will one of these girls win the free trip to Paris being\noffered by The Washington Times?\nLIEUT. COL. PAITRE AND LIEUT. COL. SCHNEIDER\nmer, president of the association, made opening ad\ndresses. Mrs. Benedict Aron and Mrs. I. F. Frisch are\nIllinois wives of delegates in attendance. Lieut. Col.\nRaoul C. Paitre and Lieut. Col. Auguste Schneider are\nTkt\nBARN SET AFIRE;\nFARMER HELD\nBERRYVILLE. Va., Sept. 28.\nA grand jury In the circuit court\nof Clark county yesterday re\nturned an indictment against\nCharles Wynkoop, county fanner,\ncharging him with setting fire to\nthe barn of Arthur Lee, which\nwas destroyed on the night of\nAugust 3. Another count was\nreturned against Wynkoop alleg\ning that he cut the telephone\npoles on Lee\u2019s property.\nThe evidence against Wynkoop\nwas gathered by insurance detec\ntives, who have worked on the\ncase from the time it was learned\nthat the telephone poles had been\ncut down.\nAttack on Hermit\nCharged to Suspect\nFREDERICKSBURG, Va., Sept.\n26.\u2014Alexander Parker, colored,\nwanted for theft and assault of\nR. L. Brown, 65-year-old hermit,\nwas arrested today. Parker was\nfound in a dark closet covered\nup by burlap bags.\nMISS GRACE M. WOODSON\nFRIDAY, SEPTEMBER \u00a36, 1980\n\u2014Times Staff Photos\nSARAH KOHLER AND CAPT. HURIGUCHI\nfrom France. Mrs. Kohler is the wife of Major W. H.\nKohler, of Milroy, Pa. Capt. Shusuke Horiguchi is a\nJapanese member of the association.\nGiert Tries Suicide,\nLeaves Money for\nDamage to Hotel\nFREDERICKSBURG. Va.,\nSept. 26.\u2014People who attempt\nsuicide in hotel rooms should\nleave money behind to pay for\nany damages they cause, is the\nbelief of S. W. Perrin, who tried\nto end his life in the Princess\nAnne Hotel, Wednesday. He\nleft money to pay the following\nhotel bill:\nSeptember J 3, HJO\nS. W. Perrin\nRnnm\nArtrtreee. Rlackeburx, Va.\nRoom (tiro niffhta) S7.e\u00ab\nCase 5.25\nTelephone I.<\u00ab\nGarage i.sn\nDamage to hotel S.OO\nTotal it'\u00bbo\n(Rill Path by Perrin)\nTWO ARE FINED\nIN RUM SALES\nROCKVILLE, Md., Sept. 26.\nLiquor cases, in which a man and\na woman were both found guilty,\nfeatured yesterday\u2019s session of\nthe Police Court.\nThe business depression was\nblamed by Herbert Allison, a res\ntaurant proprietor of Bethesda,\nMd., for his conviction on the\ncharge of possession of intoxicat\ning liquors, with iijent to sell.\nTestimony by the officers who\narrested him shows that when\nthey discovered the intoxicants,\nAllison told them that he sold\nonly a small amount, as business\nwas so bad that it was necessary\nfor him to do so, to meet his\nexpenses.\nMi?. Florence who\nlives near Norbeck. Md., was said\nto have seer which she was sell\ning, wher. her home was raided.\nShe told the officers that she\nmade the beer for the u:? of her\nfriends and herself and that that\nquantity which was seized, was\nmade for her birthday party.\nPolice testified, however, that\nwhen the raid was made in the\nafternoon, several men were there,\nnear the beer. 1\nState\u2019s Attorney Robert Peter,\njr\u201e held that it was too early\nfor the party to have started and\nthat the men were in working\nand not party clothes. Mrs.\nLeishuer was fined $75 as was\nAllison in the other case.\nMrs. Leishuer, through her at\ntorney, noted an appeal.\nFort Cumberland's\nLegion Post Elects\nCXJMBERLMir), Md., Sept. 26.\nDr. George O. Sharrett, a promi\nnent physician of this city, was\nelected commander of Fort Cum\nberland Post, No. 13. American\nLegion, for the ensuing year.\nOther officers elected were: Wil\nliam R. Burford, first vice com\nmander: Arthui- G. Fuller, sec\nond vice commander; Russell C.\nPaupe, finance officer; Ralph F\nPotter, adjutant; Charles L. Kopp,\nchaplain; C. A. Erye, sergeant-at\narms; Walter M. Fuller, historian;\nJohn E. McCarty, R. S. Copeland\nand Thomas F. Conlon, executive\ncommltte. 1\nPOLICE CHARGE\nGUN THREAT\nWINCHESTER, Va., Sept. 26.\nThe lives of two Winchester po\nlicemen were threatened last night\nwith a deadly weapon by a man\non the Northwestern grade, just\nwest of town, as they started to\narrest the man\u2019s companion, who\nwas alleged to have been driving\nan automobile while under the in\nfluence of liquor. The quick\naction of the two policemen saved\ntheir lives and resulted in the\narrest of both the would-be-as\nsailant and the alleged drunken\ndriver.\nIn answer to a complaint Night\nChief Boyd and Officer Hinkins\nstarted out after the driver. A\nshort distance from town they\ncame upon the car. The driver.\nWard Cadwallader, was out of the\nmachine and his companion, Sew\nell Cadwallader, was seated on\nthe running board.\nWhen the officers flashed their\nlights on the car. Sewell Cadwal\nlader pointed a gun at Boyd, who\nsnapped out his flashlight. The\nother policeman ran up behind\nCadwallader and grabbed the re\nvolver. The quick action of the\ntwo officers soon had them under\ncontrol.\nWard Cadwallader was docketed\non charges of driving a car while\nunder the influence of Jiquor\u2014\none-half gallon of moonshine\nbeing in the car. Sewell Cadwal\nlader is charged with transporta\ntion of liquor and assault with a\ndeadly weapon.\nLITTLE MISTAKE\nTROY, N. Y.,.Sept. 26.\u20141 t is a\ngood thing Louis Grandjean is a\npoor shot. He thought Leo Sulli\nvan, who was escorting a girl\nhome, was a burglar and fired\ntwo wild shots at him.\nilheWeU Dressed Man\n\nAnd Albert Kassan de- I\nsigning is synonymous\njm with good tailoring.\n$3.50\nWill Replace Any Broken\nAUTOMOBILE DOOR GLASS\nTIPPPETT CO.\n738 6th St. N.W. Nat. 0445\nPique 49\nPrints\nGuaranteed fast colors, trimmed\nwith contracting colors\u2014 veateea. but\ntons and piping. Sizes 14 to 4t.\nJ. B. JONES CO.\nISI9-SI G St. N. W.\naril\nRITCHIE DENIES\n\u201cMACHINE\u201d\nCHARGES\nGovernor Attacks Baltimore\nG. 0. P. Organization Before\n1,800 at Manor Club Meet\nSILVER SPRING, Md., Sept.\n26\u2014Enthusiasm dominated tne\n1.800 men and women who at\ntended the get-together meeting\nof Montgomery county Demo\ncrats at Manor Club, near Nor\nbeck, last night.\nAndrew J. \u201cCy\u201d Cummings. As\nsociate Circuit Court Judge John\nS. Newman, Robert Peter, jr.,\nGov. Albert C. Ritchie, E. Brooke\nLee, and David J. Lewis made\nstirring appeals for Democratic\nharmony in preparation for the\nelection on November 4. in the\norder named.\nRegulars Happy\nOrganization Democrats present\nwere happy not only because of\nthe unexpectedly large turnout,\nbut also because of the presence\nof approximately 200 former anti\norganization members and scores\nof women.\nState and county Republicans\nwere scored by Lee, Ritchie and\nLewis. Major E. Brooke Lee pre\nsided.\nLee presented registration fig\nures to show that the Democratic\nparty will be victorious in Mont\ngomery county and in Maryland\nin November. He said that in\nthe county there are 15,500 Demo\ncrats now registered, with 800\nnew Democrats to be added on\nregistration days next month,\nwhile there are only 8,300 or 8.400\nRepublicans in the county. This\nwould indicate, he said, a Demo\ncratic majority of approximately\n8,000 if the voters turn out.\nRobert Peter, jr., State\u2019s at\ntorney for Montgomery county,\nthe next sepaker. defended the\nrecord of the county Democrats\nand appealed for harmony. He\nwas followed by John S. Newman,\nof Frederick, candidate for elec\ntion' as associate judge in the\nSixth judicial circuit, who pleaded\nfor unity and good will. He dwelt\nlargely upon State politics.\nGovernor Ritchie replied to the\nstatement made in the Maryland\nRepublican platform that since\nhe has been governor of Mary\nland \"the power of the executive\nhas been used to develop a po\nlitical machine,\u201d and that this\nmachine \u201ccannot be broken ex\ncept by the election of the Repub\nlican nominee.\u201d\nCharges G. O. P. Machine\nGovernor Ritchie denied he has\ncreated a political machine, and\nclaimed a freedom from politics\nof governmental activity and effi\nciency in the public school sys\ntem of the State; in the adminis\ntration of the health department;\nin the conduct of the public hos\npitals and other institutions; in\nthe merit system for relation to\ngovernment employes, and in the\nmanagement of the State roads\ndepartment.\nHe charged that the Republi\ncans in the city hall in Balti\nmore have built up a machine\nthey would not exchange for the\nso-called \u201cRitchie machine.\u201d Dur\ning his 30-minute talk, the gov\nernor did not touch upon the\nprohibition question.\nIn introducing David J. Lewis,\ncandidate for the House of Repre\nsentatives, Major Lee declared\nthat he expects the county Demo\ncratic ticket to receive the votes\nof 1,500 Republicans.\nLewis spoke in behalf of the\nState and county tickets.\nW- L. High School\nLargest in State\nCLARENDON, Va.. Sept. 26.\nWhen the addition of 34 rooms\nto the Washington and Lee High\nSchool is complete, it will be the\nlargest high school in the State.\nEnrollment for the first day\npassed the 1,250 mark and it is\nexpected to be more than 1,300\nwhen a complete registration is\nreported.\nMoney Can\u2019t Buy Better Teeth\nW-A l MO. MB. AND S2O\nPlates Repaired While Yon Wait\n4,1 JT? rk Doa Mt Own Labors\ntorlee\u2014No Long Waiting\u2014No\nHigh Prices\nCrown and Bridge Work\n$5 irnn> $5\nKXTKAt TIDNS g| Ito\u2014lH V- -u\nDR. SMATHERS\nDental Mtm-ialiat\n98? SEVENTH ST. N. W.\nAcross from Goldenberg's and <>\u00bber\nPeoples Drug Store\nHonrs \u2022a.m.toS p. m. Ph. Met. \u00bbKS\u00ab\nIM","height":"30387","width":"24135"}}
